{"ts": "2026-06-07T20:14:21.917310+00:00", "update": {"model": {"messages": [{"type": "ai", "data": {"content": "### Prerequisites\n- Node.js: Node 18+ (recommended) — the Docker build uses `node:lts-alpine`.\n- Yarn 1.x (classic). The lockfile is `yarn.lock` and the repo uses yarn scripts. If you prefer npm, you can use `npm` equivalents, but the documented flow is yarn.\n- Optional: Taskfile CLI (to use `task ...` helpers), Docker (for containerized preview/build), Nginx (already used in Docker image).\n\n### Quick start: run locally (dev)\n1. Install dependencies\n   - `yarn install`\n2. Copy env for local development\n   - `cp envs/.env.local .env`  \n     The Vite config loads either `.env` or `envs/.env.<NODE_ENV>` depending on what exists; copying `envs/.env.local` to `.env` is the repo’s documented “init” step.\n3. Start dev server\n   - `yarn dev` (recommended)  \n     This runs: `cross-env NODE_ENV=local vite --host`  \n     - It will read env from `.env` (now pointing at local).\n     - Dev server port comes from `VITE_PORT` in your env (local uses `10086`).\n   - If you prefer not to copy env files, you can run the staging variant:  \n     `yarn dev:stg` (uses `NODE_ENV=stg` and reads `envs/.env.stg`).\n4. Open the app\n   - By default, local env uses `VITE_PORT=10086`, so open: `http://localhost:10086/`\n   - The dev server is started with `--host`, so you can access it from other devices on your LAN if needed (host binding can differ by OS).\n\nNotes\n- If you used Taskfile, you can do: `task init` then `task default` (but the “default” task only echoes args). The init task performs:\n  - `cp envs/.env.local .env`\n  - `yarn install`\n  - It also installs some global conventional-release tooling you can ignore for just local dev.\n\n### Build or preview for different environments\nThe repo provides multiple scripts; the important distinction is which environment (mode) you build for and what Vite will load.\n\n- Production build (default)\n  - Command: `yarn build`\n  - What it does: `vite build --mode prod`  \n    - Uses Vite mode `prod`; Vite will try to load `envs/.env.prod` (since you won’t have a `.env` during build unless you copied prod).  \n    - Output goes to `dist/` by default (not explicitly set in vite.config, so Vite uses default `dist`).\n\n- Staging build (test)\n  - Command: `yarn build:stg`\n  - What it does: `cross-env vite build --mode test`\n  - It’s unclear whether this is intentional (mode is `test` but there is no `envs/.env.test`). If you need staging env, you can either:\n    - Use `yarn dev:stg` for local staging dev, or\n    - Copy `envs/.env.stg` to `.env` and run `yarn build` so Vite reads `envs/.env.stg`.\n\n- Production build (explicit)\n  - Command: `yarn build:prod`\n  - What it does: `cross-env vite build --mode production`\n  - This mode is `production`, but env files use modes `prod`/`stg`/`local`. There may be a naming mismatch; to ensure the intended env is used, copy the desired env file to `.env` before building (e.g., `cp envs/.env.prod .env` then `yarn build`).\n\n- Preview built site locally\n  - After building, preview with: `yarn serve` (`vite preview --host`)\n  - Open the URL shown by Vite preview (commonly `http://localhost:4173` depending on Vite version).\n\n- Dockerized build/preview (container with Nginx)\n  - Build image: `docker build -t vite-react-ts-admin .`\n  - Run container: `docker run -p 8080:80 vite-react-ts-admin`\n  - Open: `http://localhost:8080`\n  - The Dockerfile copies `dist` into Nginx and uses a provided `nginx.conf`; this is a convenient way to preview production-like serving.\n\n- CI or deployment\n  - There is a script `yarn deploy` (`gh-pages -d dist`) for GitHub Pages; you may need a build step first (e.g., `yarn build`) to produce `dist`.\n  - There is a Netlify config `netlify.toml`; Netlify deploys typically run the site’s build command and publish `dist`.", "additional_kwargs": {"refusal": null}, "response_metadata": {"token_usage": 